Â Â Â }
4. Functions as first-class citizens
Kotlin treats functions as first-class citizens, which may raise questions if youâ€™re coming from Java: What does that mean, and why does it matter?
The key difference lies in Javaâ€™s limited approach â€“ its functional capabilities focus mostly on the call-site via lambdas, while the declaration-side remains tied to verbose and less intuitive functional interfaces. In Kotlin, you can define, pass, return, and compose functions without any boilerplate, making functional programming far more expressive and natural.
Java
public void doWithImage(
      URL url,Â 
      //ğŸ¤¨ Function interfaces introduce an indirection: because we donâ€™t see the signature of a Function we donâ€™t know what aÂ  BiConsumer does, unless we look it up
      BiConsumer<String, BufferedImage> f) throws IOException {
Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â f.accept(url.getFile(), ImageIO.read(url));
}

//ğŸ¤¨ Same here
public void debug(Supplier<String> f) {
Â Â Â if(isDebugEnabled()) {
Â Â Â Â Â Â logger.debug("Debug: " + f.get());
Â Â Â }
}

//ğŸ¤¨ calling no-argument lambdas is verbose
debug(() -> "expensive concat".repeat(1000));
Kotlin
fun doWithImage(
Â Â Â url: URL,
Â  //ğŸ˜ƒ Kotlin has a syntax for declaring functions: from the signature, we see what goes in and what goes outÂ 
Â Â Â f:(String, BufferedImage) -> Unit) =Â 
      f(url.file, ImageIO.read(url))

Â Â //ğŸ˜ƒ same here: nothing goes in, a String goes out
fun debug(msg: () -> String) {
Â Â Â if(isDebugEnabled) {
            logger.debug(msg())
Â Â Â }
